### JWT Authentication Flow Test
### Use this file with REST Client extension or manually with curl

### Step 1: Login as Learner
POST http://localhost:8081/api/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "learner1@example.com",
  "password": "password123"
}

### Expected Response:
# {
#   "token": "eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9...",
#   "userId": 1,
#   "email": "learner1@example.com",
#   "firstName": "Learner1",
#   "role": "LEARNER",
#   "message": "Connexion réussie"
# }

### COPY THE TOKEN FROM RESPONSE ABOVE AND PASTE IT BELOW

###

### Step 2: Get Earned Badges (Replace TOKEN and USER_ID)
GET http://localhost:8083/api/certifications-badges/earned-badges/learner/1
Authorization: Bearer YOUR_TOKEN_HERE

### Expected Response (if badges exist):
# [
#   {
#     "id": 1,
#     "badgeTemplate": {
#       "id": 3,
#       "name": "Spring Boot Silver Badge",
#       "description": "Awarded for scoring 75% or higher",
#       "examId": 102,
#       "minimumScore": 75.0
#     },
#     "learnerId": 1,
#     "awardDate": "2026-02-27",
#     "awardedBy": 0
#   }
# ]

### Expected Response (if no badges):
# []

###

### Step 3: Get Earned Certifications (Replace TOKEN and USER_ID)
GET http://localhost:8083/api/certifications-badges/earned-certifications/learner/1
Authorization: Bearer YOUR_TOKEN_HERE

### Expected Response (if certifications exist):
# [
#   {
#     "id": 1,
#     "certificationTemplate": {
#       "id": 1,
#       "title": "Spring Boot Fundamentals",
#       "description": "Certification for completing Spring Boot exam",
#       "examId": 102
#     },
#     "learnerId": 1,
#     "issueDate": "2026-02-27",
#     "expiryDate": "2028-02-27",
#     "awardedBy": 0
#   }
# ]

###

### Step 4: Test with Wrong Learner ID (should return 403 FORBIDDEN)
GET http://localhost:8083/api/certifications-badges/earned-badges/learner/999
Authorization: Bearer YOUR_TOKEN_HERE

### Expected Response:
# 403 FORBIDDEN

###

### Step 5: Test without Token (should return 401 UNAUTHORIZED)
GET http://localhost:8083/api/certifications-badges/earned-badges/learner/1

### Expected Response:
# 401 UNAUTHORIZED
# {"error": "Invalid or expired token"}

###

### Step 6: Award a badge via auto-award system (to create test data)
POST http://localhost:8083/api/certifications-badges/exam-integration/process-exam-result
Content-Type: application/json
X-Internal-Api-Key: exam-service-dev-key

{
  "learnerId": 1,
  "examId": 102,
  "score": 75.0,
  "maxScore": 100.0
}

### Expected Response:
# {
#   "learnerId": 1,
#   "examId": 102,
#   "percentage": 75.0,
#   "passed": true,
#   "certificationAwarded": true,
#   "certificationId": 1,
#   "badgeAwarded": true,
#   "badgeId": 1,
#   "message": "Exam score: 75.00%. Passed! Certification awarded. Badge awarded for high achievement!"
# }

###

### TROUBLESHOOTING

### Check Auth Service Health
GET http://localhost:8081/actuator/health

###

### Check Certification-Badge Service Health
GET http://localhost:8083/actuator/health

###

### Verify JWT Secret Configuration
# Both services must have the same jwt.secret value:
# - Backend/auth-service/src/main/resources/application.yml
# - Backend/certification-badge-service/src/main/resources/application.yml

###

### Common Issues:
# 1. 401 UNAUTHORIZED → Token missing, invalid, or expired
# 2. 403 FORBIDDEN → User doesn't have permission (wrong learner ID)
# 3. CORS error → Backend CORS configuration issue
# 4. Connection refused → Service not running
# 5. Empty array [] → No badges/certifications awarded yet (run Step 6)
